{
  "text": "It can be shown that this equation uniquely defines R(x) as a formal power series in t with coefficients in xQ [x] . Equation (7) is the standard result of the kernel method. Still, as in [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , we want to apply here the obstinate kernel method. That is, we shall not content ourselves with (7), but we shall go on producing pairs (X, Y ) that cancel the kernel and use the information they provide on the series R(x). This obstination was inspired by the book [CITATION_3] by Fayolle, Iasnogorodski and Malyshev, and more precisely by Section 2.4 of this book, where one possible way to obtain such pairs is described (even though the analytic context is different). We give here an alternative construction. Figure 3) . A geometric description of this orbit is provided in Figure 4 .",
